{
  "doc_id": "48514",
  "text": "Patients with severe underlying cardiopulmonary diseases, such as chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, cardiomyopathy, or congenital heart disease, may be at risk for severe hypoxemia following ascent to high altitude [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Because high altitude simulation testing [CITATION_3] may not always be feasible prior to their planned sojourn and because travel with supplemental oxygen is logistically difficult, many of these patients may wish to monitor their oxygen saturation using a portable device or by periodic clinic visits upon arrival and use the measured values as a guide for further action [CITATION_4] . No data suggest this strategy improves outcomes at high altitude, but it is a prudent approach in light of the logistical issues previously noted and for the potential of detecting clinical deterioration in certain patients following arrival.",
